      "nodeid" : "1",
      "nodetitle" : "Page Two",
      "storypartial" : `Back to sixth grade, where Albert is in class, writing a history test. Albert never doubts that he will get a perfect score, although he hasn’t studied for this test either. Not because he forgot, but because Albert never studies before the tests anymore, he studies afterwards. Albert reads the question to himself slowly, making sure to memorize the question clearly in his mind. Albert has often thought about how useful it would be if he had a photographic memory, but he accepts that what he has is probably infinitely more valuable anyways. The question is asking him for the date on which the declaration of independence was adopted by Congress. Albert knows the day is July fourth, but he doesn’t know the year. At least, he doesn’t know it yet.
	1776 comes his own voice, speaking inside his head. Albert writes down July fourth, 1776. Next question, how many original colonies were there when the declaration was signed? Thirteen. Albert writes down thirteen. How many people signed it? Fifty-six. Albert writes down fifty-six, and so on and so forth for every question. Albert is the first person in his class to finish, as he usually is. He hands in his test, and goes back to his desk to wait out the rest of the period.
	As soon as Albert gets home he goes on his computer and searches up the declaration of independence. Right on cue, he hears his own voice in his head, asking when it was signed. He answers his past self, 1776. Thirteen original colonies. Fifty-six signatories. King George III. Albert keeps looking up the information required by his past self until the voice quiets and he hands in the test to his teacher. The Albert in history class goes to sit down at his desk, and the Albert at home closes the article he had been reading and opens up a new browser page, this one displaying a list of stock prices. Albert transitions from being the future Albert to being the past Albert effortlessly, and listens as the voice of himself in a few years tells him which buttons to click.
	By the time Albert makes it to high school he is richer than his parents, although they don’t know it. Albert saves most of the money, keeping it in an account which is managed by a man who has never seen Albert’s face or heard his voice. Lately the manager has taken to investing in the same stocks that Albert invests in, and he hasn’t been sorry. Albert isn’t always right, although he could have been. The future Albert understands that picking a winner every time is the most suspicious thing you can do, and so he tempers the past Albert’s gains with the occasional loss. The present Albert makes sure that the future Albert doesn’t get arrested while at the same time making sure that the past Albert aces all of his tests.
	The present Albert is fifteen, although it could just as easily be said that the present Albert is all of the ages he will ever be and has ever been. Albert never thinks too hard about the fluid nature of time as it applies to him because it gives him a headache, and because on some level deep down he is afraid that if he tries to make sense of it the ability will leave him. Albert is afraid of what he would be without every other Albert there to help him. Without the future Alberts he would do far worse at school, and without the past Alberts he wouldn’t be as wealthy as he is. In short, without his strange and miraculous ability he would be normal, and that scares Albert more than anything in the world. The thought that because he has the ability in the future it follows that he doesn’t lose the ability in the present helps to console him on the surface of his thoughts, but in that deep place in his mind that proof does little to assuage his fear of being average. What Albert is most afraid of is that he might become the only Albert, isolated in time from all the other Alberts, alone.`,
