      "nodeid" : "2",
      "nodetitle" : "Page Three",
      "storypartial" : `Albert fears loneliness partly because he doesn’t remember what it felt like. He has few memories that predate that math test in third grade, and ever since that day he has always been surrounded by the million other Alberts spread out across the entire span of his life. They work together beautifully, because everything they do for each other they’re really doing for themselves. Albert exercises regularly and eats well so that the future Alberts will be healthy and strong, and Albert always makes sure that he helps out the past Alberts whenever they run into problems.
	Albert’s ability evolves when he is fifteen. He is in ninth grade, a high school student. It has been six years since Albert first spoke to himself across time itself during that third grade math test. Following the advice of his future selves, Albert has tried to maintain a low profile, but he’s a fifteen year old boy. Albert is a teenager with an ego to match, which sometimes makes it hard for him to listen to his elder selves. On this day, he sees a kid he doesn’t know being bullied by three older kids, tenth or eleventh graders. They are bigger than he is, and he is bigger than the kid they’re picking on. From where Albert is standing, it looks like they’re trying to extort money out of him, or maybe they’re just pushing him around; it’s hard to tell from that angle. Albert hasn’t known even the slightest of unintentional failures in six years, and this makes him confident. Albert strides over and tells them to pick on somebody their own size. The largest kid, clearly the ring leader, turns to face Albert and his lackeys turn with him. Their victim clutches his backpack to his chest and shrinks backwards against the wall they’d pinned him to.
	The ringleader gets right up in Albert’s face, glaring down at him, trying to look intimidating. Albert can smell his breath; make out the individual pores on the guy’s face. This Albert doesn’t know what the kid’s problem is, although another Albert tells him the kid’s parents are going through a divorce. The present Albert doesn’t know when that information comes from, nor does he care about why this guy feels the need to pick on others. Albert is angry, that dangerous type of anger possessed by those who firmly believe they’re in the right. Some call it righteous indignation, but that doesn’t matter to the present Albert either. Even being stared down by three older kids who are all bigger than him doesn’t make Albert afraid. Albert fears only one thing, and these kids have nothing to do with that. When the biggest kid, the leader of their little trio, sucker punches Albert in the stomach, he has no idea how big of a mistake he just made. Albert has never been hit before, and having the wind knocked out of him is a surprise. He falls to his hands and knees, panting heavily, and time itself changes as its victims laugh.
	When Albert gets back up, he is both fifteen and thirty years old. His fifteen year old self is burning with fury, and that fury is flowing all the way down the time stream to his twenty year old self, who immediately takes up kickboxing. Ten years later Albert is an expert at it, and it is that thirty year old Albert who actually travels up the time stream against the current which is laden with the fury of the fifteen year old Albert. The fact that this kid’s parents are getting divorced, and the accompanying knowledge that the kid is probably miserable no longer means anything to either of the two Alberts present at that moment. Fifteen year old Albert stands up, smiles, and the three would be bullies take an involuntary step backwards as the thirty year old Albert unleashes fifteen year old Albert’s unbridled rage.
	It is the first time that an Albert has actually moved through time, instead of just sending words. Thirty year old Albert’s mastery of kickboxing, even when used by fifteen year old Albert’s body, is effective. As the victimized kid watches in open mouthed awe, Albert moves like water, jumping around and peppering his three opponents with jabs. The fight is finished as quickly as it was started, and soon all three kids are moaning on the ground. As thirty year old Albert returns to when he came from, fifteen year old Albert walks over to the bullies’ intended victim and helps him up. The kid thanks Albert profusely, and Albert can see that even though the other boy is the same age as him, Albert has become his hero. Albert feels uncomfortable about it, but he becomes friends with the boy all the same.
	The boy Albert saved that day is named Bill, and the two of them quickly become inseparable. In tenth grade Albert joins the debate club, as does Bill. Bill is smart, and has a natural affinity for words. The two of them make something more than just a good team, together they are unstoppable. Bill listens when Albert suggests which arguments their opponents are likely to use, and crafts retorts designed specifically to dismantle those points. Albert doesn’t tell Bill how he knows what he does, and Bill never asks, but Bill understands that there is something fundamentally different between him and Albert. Unlike Albert’s parents and teachers however, Bill is observant, and he can see that Albert is not just a genius. In fact, Bill can tell that Albert is probably not even as smart as him, but Albert knows things. Albert is never, ever surprised by anything. Albert always knows what’s going to happen next.`,
