      "nodeid" : "4",
      "nodetitle" : "Page Five",
      "storypartial" : `This is a watershed moment for Albert; the first time he really makes a decision that affects his own future. In the past Albert has never really had to make a choice. Even saving Bill was a logical progression of events that had always and would always and presently was taking place, depending on when exactly you were looking at it from. The present Albert is noticing that he is attracted to this girl. He wants to say yes, to make her his girlfriend. Albert in one month agrees wholeheartedly, telling the present Albert that she is the greatest thing he has ever seen. Albert in two months also agrees, although he is more cautious, telling the Albert of one month in the future not to objectify her so much, and telling the present Albert to go for it. The problem is that the Albert three months into the future says no. Albert three months from now is going through his first break up. The Albert three months into the future has never felt anything even close to this before. He has never lost at anything; he has never made a mistake. Now he’s been dumped and it’s shaken him. The Alberts of one and two months into the future ask if it really isn’t worth it to have three months of happiness and great experiences. Albert three months from now says the price is too high. All the while the girl, who Albert knows without having to ask is named Cindy, is waiting nervously for his response. Albert looks at her, knowing that in three months she’ll dump him if he says yes, saying that he’s too weird for her. Cindy will tell him that there’s something wrong with him, that he’s right too often, that he doesn’t understand emotions properly. Cindy will say that he doesn’t understand how she feels and she will be right, but she won’t say it if he says no right here in this debate hall.
	Albert tells Cindy that he’s sorry but he’s not ready for a relationship. Cindy looks crestfallen but she nods and walks away quickly, her face blushing red in embarrassment. In a lot of ways the Cindy of that moment is a lot like the Albert in three months. Cindy is a pretty cheerleader, as unused to losing as Albert, and she’s just been rejected by somebody objectively less popular than she is. She doesn’t know what to make of it. As she leaves, Bill returns from where he was watching a respectful distance away, and asks Albert what the hell is wrong with him. Albert replies that he doesn’t know, but it’s a lie that even Bill can see through. Bill knows that Albert knows what’s wrong with him, just as he knew how to win their debate this afternoon.
	When he gets home that evening Albert goes to his room and lies down on his bed. Usually he would be hanging out with Bill around this time, catching a movie or hanging out at the mall, but today he says he had some thinking to do. Bill says he understood and leaves Albert alone. As he lies splayed out on his back, staring at the ceiling, Albert thinks about what happened that day.
	On their way home Bill asks him why he didn’t give that girl a chance. Albert mutters cryptically that her name is Cindy and that he did give her a chance, which is as close as he had ever come to sharing the truth that separates him from the rest of his peers. If Bill catches that little slip he doesn’t show it. Now that he is alone in his room, Albert has a little meeting with the Alberts from one, two, and three months ahead. These Alberts are not the same Alberts who had spoken to him about their experiences with Cindy. Those Alberts are gone, dispersed into a diverging time stream, their memories and experiences lost forever. The problem is that the present Albert remembers what they have told him, and so do the three new Alberts from the future. The entire experience is very strange. Thinking that the only parts of those three months that would never happen exist only as the words he has gleaned from those versions of himself that had dissipated fills Albert with a strange type of depression. Albert wonders if his past self would ever make a choice that he hadn’t made and eliminate him from the time stream. The thought makes him sad but not afraid; if his destiny is to be erased by himself then he will accept it as the other Alberts accepted it. Fate might hang over his head every day like the blade of a guillotine, he realizes, but he would be or had been or was presently his own executioner, and somehow that makes it alright.`,
