      "nodeid" : "6",
      "nodetitle" : "Page Seven",
      "storypartial" : `It is important to note that the future Alberts all agreed that if not the best possible outcome, the events that unfold after Albert makes the connection between Bill and his other classmates is what should have happened. None of them explain to Albert before he challenges the math teacher what the difference is between that man and Billy, because even after what happens they don’t fully understand what the difference is. To the Alberts that exist both before and after the incident the math teacher is just a more aggressive Bill who causes some level of discomfort to twenty three other Bills. Before Albert meets Bill, he doesn’t think about other people at all. After Albert meets Bill, he assumes that everyone is basically like Bill. That is not to say that he likes them as much as he likes the first Bill, because the only person he really cares about other than his parents is Bill, the original. Essentially though, in Albert’s mind Bill represents everyone, including the math teacher. The math teacher proves himself to be different from Bill though, and that distancing from the archetypal good person named Bill that exists in Albert’s mind allows Albert to say something to the math teacher that he would never have said to Bill or anyone like Bill.
	Albert stands up and walks to the front of the class, noticing that the math teacher’s eyes have widened and not really caring. It’s already too late for him, as Albert knows. He isn’t sorry for what is about to happen, especially because the math teacher’s complicity will be his downfall. Albert gives a short synopsis of the events that led to this quiz to the class, speaking in the clear voice Bill recognizes from the debate team. The members of the class pay quiet attention, not interrupting. They all have at least some idea of who Albert is, and a few have directly experienced the effect of his charisma. None of them, including Billy, understand that he isn’t so successful because of his charisma, but actually he is charismatic because everything he does is a success. After Albert finishes explaining that the teacher has given them a test designed to prove that Albert is not as good at math as he claims to be, Albert turns to the teacher and gives him an ultimatum. Albert says that to prove the test is possible, the teacher should write it at the same time as the students and the test should be graded by an independent body. The teacher agrees, and why would he not? The teacher has a master’s degree and Albert is a high school student, albeit also an alleged cheater and possibly—although the teacher would never admit it—a prodigy.
	The class watches in silence as the math teacher takes out an extra copy of the test and unbeknownst to all the present observers save Albert, decides his own fate.  The test is made up of questions taken from old SAT’s designed to be challenging. The teacher hasn’t gone over the answers beforehand; he did not foresee Albert’s challenge the way Albert had foreseen the teacher’s. Still, the teacher is confident both in his own abilities and in the randomness of his selected questions. He is satisfied that unless Albert somehow memorized all the answers to every SAT math question before the test there is no way for him to know the answers. The teacher also thinks that Albert couldn’t have even known where he would get the questions from. The teacher assumes that there is no way for Albert to cheat on this test, and as he begins to write the test he created, his mind wanders to a fantasy of Albert being exposed and suspended.
	What it really came down to was that the teacher didn’t go through the proper channels. That was the explanation on paper for what happened. A teacher can’t rise to a student’s dare or test students on material not covered in class. The other explanation for the teacher’s resignation was that not only did Albert prove his allegation of cheating false by once again achieving a perfect score on the test; the teacher made a mistake and actually scored worse than Albert. Albert had made the teacher’s accusations public knowledge, and when the teacher was outperformed on his own test he faced ridicule and backlash from students, parents and faculty alike. The teacher didn’t quite resign in disgrace but it was close. The teacher handled the situation poorly and left the school to teach elsewhere, the event a black eye for his resume. Albert doesn’t think too much about it, to him the teacher wasn’t like Bill anymore and therefor he doesn’t really care what happens to him. The notion that Albert both lost a man his job and that technically he actually was cheating on all of those tests doesn’t bother him. Albert reasons that high school is supposed to both prepare you for, and judge your aptitude for, the real world, and his ability is a talent that will come in handy there. To Albert his ability to communicate with his past and future selves is like any other innate talent, there to be used.`,
